   3. FAQ — Editorial accordion
   ═══════════════════════════════════════════════════════════ #}
<section class="ep-faq">
  <div class="ep-faq-inner">
    <div>
      <span class="ep-chapter-label">Common Questions</span>
      <h2 class="ep-faq-title">Retirement Planning FAQ</h2>
      <p class="ep-faq-sub">Essential information about federal retirement preparation, timing, and procedures for a smooth transition.</p>
      <a href="/contact/" class="ep-btn-ghost">Get Personal Guidance</a>
    </div>
    <div>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I start planning my federal retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Start planning your federal retirement at least 5 years before your intended retirement date. This gives you time to optimize your FERS pension calculation, maximize TSP contributions, ensure FEHB eligibility, review FEGLI needs, plan Social Security coordination, and make any necessary adjustments to your federal benefits. Early planning allows you to take advantage of strategies like military buyback, sick leave maximization, and high-3 salary optimization that require time to implement properly.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">What forms do I need to submit for federal retirement? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>The primary form is SF-3107 (Application for Immediate Retirement - FERS) or SF-2801 for CSRS employees. You'll also need SF-3102 (Designation of Beneficiary - FERS), health insurance enrollment forms if making changes, TSP withdrawal forms, and potentially survivor benefit elections. Submit your retirement application to your HR office at least 60 days before your intended retirement date (90 days is recommended). Each agency may have additional forms or requirements, so check with your HR department early in the process.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">How do I ensure I meet the 5-year FEHB rule? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>To carry FEHB into retirement, you must be enrolled for 5 consecutive years immediately before retirement. Check your personnel records to verify continuous enrollment. If you have any gaps (such as periods covered under a spouse's plan), you may not be eligible. Limited exceptions exist for military service or involuntary loss of spousal coverage. If you're close to but don't meet the 5-year requirement, consider extending your retirement date to qualify, as FEHB is extremely valuable in retirement.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">Should I take a lump sum TSP withdrawal or monthly payments? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>This depends on your overall financial situation, other retirement income sources, investment knowledge, and estate planning goals. TSP offers four withdrawal options: lump sum, monthly installments, TSP annuity, or a combination. Consider factors like investment management capability, need for guaranteed income, tax implications, and estate planning. Many retirees benefit from keeping some money in the low-cost TSP while taking systematic withdrawals. Federal employees who separate at age 55+ can access TSP without the 10% early withdrawal penalty.</p></div>
      </button>
      <button class="ep-faq-item" onclick="this.classList.toggle('active')">
        <span class="ep-faq-q">When should I claim Social Security as a federal retiree? <span class="ep-faq-icon">+</span></span>
        <div class="ep-faq-a"><p>Federal employees have unique considerations for Social Security timing. Key factors include: (1) The FERS supplement ends at age 62, potentially creating an income gap if you delay Social Security, (2) Your FERS pension provides some income security, allowing flexibility in timing, (3) Delayed retirement credits (8% per year from full retirement age to 70), and (4) Tax implications of combined FERS and Social Security income. With WEP/GPO now eliminated, many federal retirees benefit from claiming at full retirement age (66-67) to bridge the gap when the FERS supplement ends, but individual situations vary significantly.</p></div>
      </button>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

